text:
breast ironing is yet another symptom of a world rife with gender equality.breast ironing is the practice of flattening a young girlâ€™s chest, often with hot stones or spatulas, to stop them from growing.
parents will often force their daughters to undergo breast ironing in an attempt to protect them from sexual harassment and rape.Â but, like female genital mutilation (fgm), the consequences for health can be severe: infections, difficulty breastfeeding, and an increased likelihood ofÂ breast cancerÂ and cysts.
the practice is also known as â€œbreast flatteningâ€ or â€œbreast sweeping,â€Â in order to prevent girlsâ€™ breasts from growing, mothers may alsoÂ wrap bandagesÂ tightly around their daughtersâ€™ chests."every morning, before going to school, my mom makes me lift up my top so she can make sure i haven't taken my bandage off,â€ aÂ 14-year-old cameroonian girl said.
â€œbreast ironing,â€ .while studies have found that â€œbreast ironingâ€ isÂ practiced inÂ chad, guinea bissau, togo, and benin, it is most common in cameroon, whereÂ nearly a quarterÂ of girls and women have had their breasts â€œironed.â€Â casesÂ have also been reported in the uk and as many as 1,000 girls from west african immigrant communities in the uk are believed to have undergone â€œbreast ironing,â€Â the week reported.
though these mothers may have good intentions, â€œbreast ironingâ€ is unlikely to address the larger, systemic problems they are hoping to solve: violence against women and gender inequality.
rather than trusting men to respect womenâ€™s bodies and their choices, these mothers believe they must make their daughters less attractive to protect them.
when girls and women are seen as equals and are empowered to make choices for themselves, choices that are respected by those around them, the need to â€œprotectâ€ girls through â€œbreast ironingâ€ will be eliminated.
***

text:
vereniging montium vindt het erg belangrijk om stil te staan bij de rechten van de vrouw en haar positie in de maatschappij. op 27 februari vindt hierom het volgende evenement alweer plaats in het hart van den haag, namelijk leiden university college. dit evenement zal zich richten op female genital mutilation (fgm), specifiek in de kurdistan regional government (krg, ofwel koerdistan regionale overheid) in irak en de koerdische gemeenschap. 
wat is fgm? wat voor maatregelen zijn er genomen, vanuit de krg en/of organisaties, om dit te stoppen? hoe dicht zijn we bij het uitroeien van deze praktijken in de koerdische gemeenschap? wat voor effect heeft dit op het leven van een persoon? belangrijke, maar ook gevoelige vragen worden beantwoord. het belooft een leerzaam en indrukwekkend evenement te worden. tickets zullen binnenkort verkrijgbaar zijn!

text: music will always be my identity. this photo was taken at media city, salford, in the autumn of 2013, which was quite a challenging time for me mentally (which continued to go downhill for me until 2018) as i was trying to disguise my psychosis and an eating disorder. trying to pursue your passion when youâ€™re very mentally unwell is nigh on impossible, and so anything musical came to a complete stop and iâ€™m not gonna lie, it ripped my heart out. my psychosis (diagnosed schizophrenia) got so bad that i couldnâ€™t even hold onto what i was thinking never mind write some lyrics. i did manage performing with a wedding band (probably due to muscle memory) but apart from that my solo music was non existent. i was so used to my life being music every day that this shit felt like utter hell on earth. i needed independence for my wellbeing, so i got my own place two years ago. unfortunately, after living on my own for less than 4 months, i was raped which (obviously) had a profound effect on me. to this day i suffer the consequences of a scumbagâ€™s actions. nightmares, flashbacks, hyper vigilance and paranoia (like i needed anymore of that). due to shame and guilt, i purposefully avoided writing music as i didnâ€™t want to put salt on my already painful wounds. so here i am with complex mental health issues but guess what? iâ€™m ready for writing again. iâ€™m ready to delve into my subconscious and drag the pain out, via music.

text:
we are because of her. who is she? she is recy taylor!  she stood up and sought justice against 6 rapists, who were white supremacists, in a time where it could mean death for her and her family. recy taylor paved the way so that we could seek justice today. ğŸ‘‡ğŸ¾ #dontlookaway this is the history of rape and survivors standing up for themselves. this is #intersectionality. never forget that rape was and is used as a weapon of torture, control, and subjugation by those in power.
....
faced with few options for legal recourse, african american women chose to share their stories, drawing on a longstanding history of testimony and truth-telling to shed light on their pain. â€œwhile survivors of sexualized violence rarely received justice in southern courts,â€ mcguire writes, â€œblack women like recy taylor who were raped by white men in the 1940s used their voices as weapons against white supremacy.â€ it wasnâ€™t until 2011, nearly 60 years after the case, that the state of alabama issued a formal apology to taylor for her treatment by the stateâ€™s legal system. â€œ[taylor] was an american hero and an alabama treasure who spoke up in the face of racism, hate and sexual violence,â€ alabama rep. terri a. sewell said in a statement. â€œby standing up to injustice over six decades ago, recy taylor inspired generations of men and women to hold perpetrators of sexual violence accountable.â€ taylor died in abbeville on dec. 21, 2017, three weeks after the release ofÂ the rape of recy taylor. she was 97.

though recy taylorâ€™s case did not succeed in the short term, the fact that women like taylor were telling their stories at a time of pronounced stigma and intimidation drew nationwide attention to issues of racial violence, mobilizing communities and building coalitions that would become the pillars of the civil rights movement.
- the national museum of african american history & culture (smithsonian)

text:
keep in mind i still have not experienced everything. 
i have never experienced the horrid strains of war.
i have never experienced discrimination based on my race, gender, or sexual orientation.
i have never experienced the painful process of fighting cancer.

my point is this. life throws obstacles in front of us to test our mental and physical fortitude. it is how we overcome these obstacles we become stronger, wiser, and more resilient. 
life does not care about what job title you have or what measly possessions you obtain. all life cares about is how you get from a to b. and when youâ€™ve finally hit the final destination of life. you are now allowed to look back and say. â€œthat was my life!â€ â€œi lived through that!â€ â€œi overcame that!â€
â€œi built that!â€
â€œi protected that!â€
â€œi preserved that!â€
and finally...
â€œi am that!â€ good luck and love one another. because love is all we have.

i dedicate this post to the most important person of my life. the person who taught me what love means. what love is. my hero, and my greatest inspiration. 
today would have been her birthday. she past away 11 years ago. 
cheers to the greatest generation for leading our way to change.
#inspirationalquotes #inspiration #inspirational #changtheworld #change #metoo #blacklivesmatter #movement
#blackandwhite #love #loveyourself #peace

text:
for #strongsaturday we are honoring the founder of the #metoo movement, tarana burke, a black activist hailing from harlem.

in 1997, burke was a youth worker primarily serving young black girls and girls of color. after listening to a 13-year-old girl describe her experience of sexual abuse, ms. burke recalled, â€œi didnâ€™t have a response or a way to help her in that moment, and i couldnâ€™t even say â€˜me too.â€™ â€ burke then went on to create the nonprofit just be inc. (from their site):
_
â€œfounded in 2006, just be inc. is a youth organization focused on the health, well being and wholeness of young women of color. in the face of media, music and pop culture that increasingly diminish the importance, worth, and esteem ofÂ girls and women, particularly women of color, our organization deals specifically with the range of issues teen and pre-teen girls are faced with daily. our programs center around empowerment and guidance for girls as they grow and begin to define themselves.â€
_
over the past year, burke has been dedicated to making sure the me too movement stays on track and fulfills its missionâ€” connecting survivors to resources that will aid in their healing, not just resharing stories of trauma. â€œwe donâ€™t believe in collecting stories of peopleâ€™s trauma because i donâ€™t think the trauma should be curated. we believe in sharing peoplesâ€™ stories of healing. when you start talking about what youâ€™ve done to cope and how you have developed practices around healing, thatâ€™s something that people need to see.â€
_
thank you to tarana burke for founding the #metoo movement. for being strong. for speaking up. and for showing so many people they can turn their stories into action and activism. link to donate to just be inc in our stories.

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
throughout the committee hearing, several republican senators including ted cruz and thom tillis pointed to the obama campaignâ€™s use of facebook data, to highlight the fact that such practices are bipartisan.

however, people who downloaded the obama campaign app were aware they were using a political app. by contrast, the data obtained by cambridge analytica was obtained via a personality quiz application whose users had no idea their data would be used by a political campaign.

cambridge analytica improperly obtained the personal information of millions of facebook users to build profiles of us voters in order to target them with personalised political advertisements, via a related uk-based entity called scl elections.
.
- we exploited facebook to harvest millions of peopleâ€™s profiles, said wylie in march. - and built models to exploit what we knew about them and target their inner demons. that was the basis the entire company was built on.

wylie has previously told mps at a british select committee that the eu referendum was won through fraud after vote leave allegedly used a network of companies to get round election spending laws. he said he thought there â€œcould have been a different outcome had there not been, in my view, cheatingâ€. he also met privately with house democrats in april, but wednesdayâ€™s hearing was his first public appearance before us lawmakers.

olivia solon
the guardian

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
christopher wylie, who worked with a cambridge university academic to obtain the data, told the observer: â€œwe exploited facebook to harvest millions of peopleâ€™s profiles. and built models to exploit what we knew about them and target their inner demons. that was the basis the entire company was built on.â€ documents seen by the observer, and confirmed by a facebook statement, show that by late 2015 the company had found out that information had been harvested on an unprecedented scale. however, at the time it failed to alert users and took only limited steps to recover and secure the private information of more than 50 million individuals.

the data was collected through an app called thisisyourdigitallife, built by academic aleksandr kogan, separately from his work at cambridge university. through his company global science research (gsr), in collaboration with cambridge analytica, hundreds of thousands of users were paid to take a personality test and agreed to have their data collected for academic use.

however, the app also collected the information of the test-takersâ€™ facebook friends, leading to the accumulation of a data pool tens of millions-strong. facebookâ€™s â€œplatform policyâ€ allowed only collection of friendsâ€™ data to improve user experience in the app and barred it being sold on or used for advertising. the discovery of the unprecedented data harvesting, and the use to which it was put, raises urgent new questions about facebookâ€™s role in targeting voters in the us presidential election. it comes only weeks after indictments of 13 russians by the special counsel robert mueller which stated they had used the platform to perpetrate â€œinformation warfareâ€ against the us.

carole cadwalladr & emma graham-harrison
the guardian

text:
rosemary mesa-desplas performing a spoken word piece at last weekâ€™s opening reception. the exhibition is on view today, thu-sun, 12-6pm through feb 24.
.
.
amos eno gallery is pleased to present jane anger, an exhibition of new works by rosemary meza-desplas. jane anger features hand-sewn human hair drawings, watercolors and onsite installations. rosemary meza-desplasâ€™ figurative artworks emphasize line and movement. the title refers to a 16th century pamphlet published in england titled jane anger, her protection for women. an opening reception will be held on friday, february 1 from 7-9 pm at the galleryâ€™s location at 56 bogart street in brooklyn, ny. 
meza-desplas, also a spoken word performer, will present her piece titled intervals of anger at the opening reception. she will perform a poem every fifteen minutes in conjunction with an artwork in the exhibition. 
meza-desplas explores the concept of anger as a tool for change by juxtaposing found imagery from social media, art history and mass media. she is interested in how the social movements, womenâ€™s marches and #metoo, harnessed anger in order to forefront an array of gender-based burdens. 
this exhibition includes meza-desplasâ€™ most recent drawings which incorporate her gray hair. she has been sewing with her own hair since 2000. her hair is hand-sewn into a variety of grounds with small embroidery needles. meza-desplasâ€™ decision to collect, sort and utilize hair as a vehicle for art-making is informed by socio-cultural symbolism, feminism and body issues, and religious symbolism. hair embodies a dichotomy: it can be sexy and engaging to people, on the other hand, it can be repulsive â€“ like a hair in your soup or a hair on your hotel pillow. there are religious connotations to hair which coincide with symbolism reflecting strength, sensuality and reverence; such as delila cutting off samsonâ€™s hair and mary magdalen washing the feet of jesus with her hair. .

text:
one in five women and one in 71 men will be raped at some point in their lives

in the u.s., one in three women and one in six men experienced some form of contact sexual violence in their lifetime

51.1% of female victims of rape reported being raped by an intimate partner and 40.8% by an acquaintance 
52.4% of male victims report being raped by an acquaintance and 15.1% by a stranger

almost half (49.5%) of multiracial women and over 45% of american indian/alaska native women were subjected to some form of contact sexual violence in their lifetime 
91% of victims of rape and sexual assault are female, and nine percent are male 
in eight out of 10 cases of rape, the victim knew the perpetrator

eight percent of rapes occur while the victim is at work
.
.

text:
feedback from sgbv training (2/9/19)

from today's workshop, i learnt that our gender is only known by us(self). some may be male but their expression to the world may be like feminine, same goes to girls. even though they appear to be feminine when they are male, the mind knows that the gender is still male.(female as well). the other thing that i learnt was speaking up. when we are abused in terms of sexual abused, domestic violence or any other, we need to speak up and share it with the people whom can be trusted or make a report. we must not be ashamed if it happens. if we are ashamed and keep it to ourselves, we might lose our lives.
it was a good experience to attend the sgbv seminar.i was quite shocked when we discussed about sexual harassment.it can occur in in places like factories, schools, colleges and the music business.
sexual harassment is unwanted and not to be tolerated. there are people who use their power to force someone who's weaker to make them satisfied by words,actions or even more.it is very important to know that women have also rights.women should not be afraid but to have courage to fight back.we also learn how to use pea(psychological first aid) i think it will be very useful for our community.in our community, most women are not educated and they do not know what are their rights.when they are abuse or bullied they don't dare to say or they think it is a culture so they can not do anything about it.so,i do really hope this society will change and i hope i can be part of this changes maker.
i've learned alot from the training. 
#mewro #togetherwearestronger #metoo #wao #aam #stopdomesticviolence #stoptheviolence #womenpower #womenrights

text:
the health of our society can be measured by how "honest, empatheic and understanding we can be with each other. and if we cannot speak openly about the crimes that have damaged us, the entire society suffers." ~ winnie m. li

there are so many artworks that tell the untold story of sexualised violence against jewish women during the holocaust. its not only important to break the silence of these incidents to establish a more nuanced understanding of experiences in holocaust narratives, but it is also important for understanding later genocides and to break this cycle. my ma dissertation focused on artworks from the remember the women's institute's group art exhibition, 'violated!' (2018). the exhibition created a public space that challanged the viewers to confront the present silence on genocide and sexualized violence.

text:
"i learned to smile when i felt like crying" ğŸ˜” this was a post made that caught my eye. as i read through the comments, my heart ached. it aches for all those individuals surfing with depression, anxiety, paranoia, and any other debilitating mental illness. it aches for those who have been told & taught that crying is wrong or associated with weakness. it aches for those who grew up their entire lives with misconceptions about this much needed outlet. crying is not an emotion. it is a form of expression. crying does not make you weak, it makes you balanced. it is a neccessary experience that allows you to feel and process. this is a perfect example of a social norm that is not normal at all. and many fall victim to this defective concept. this is very harmful for all people, but especially our mental health community. stop promoting this detrimental mindset and start supporting the healthy ways to express and cope with your emotions.
.

gop is dead. gop remains dead. and we have killed him. how shall we comfort ourselves, the murderers of all murderers? what was holiest and mightiest of all that the world has yet owned has bled to death under our knives: who will wipe this blood off us? what water is there for us to clean ourselves? what festivals of atonement, what sacred games shall we have to invent? is not the greatness of this deed too great for us? must we ourselves not become gods simply to appear worthy of it?

text: i remember being 9 and coming home getting my dads .38 special that he got from a coworker pulling it from the leather holster with its old english lettering. thinking i've had enough of life, i had been molested for years already been given drugs and knew what true pain and loneliness was. i had no one to talk to or to share my sadness with. i new i was soft even at that age, so i covered things with anger and negativity. i never told anyone until i was 17 and not by choice, it was the strength of my brother who had seen enough people protected at the cost of others being broken. i remember lieing saying  nothing happend to me then going and smoking so much crack that i would go from blacked out to waking up still with the pipe in my mouth. i don't even know why i'm posting this except maybe someone sees there kid start to spiral down in 5th grade and they will understand maybe it's more complex than just bullying or peers that maybe there is something pushing them to darkness. maybe another grown ass man sees it and knows he's not alone. but theres my shit fuck it. #onedayatatime #broken #struggle #truth #mylife #anxiety #anger #mentalbreakdown #innocencelost #suicide #realtalk #alone #talktoyourkids #metoo

text:
herstory is our story - an ongoing feature of women in the twin cities theater community responding to, "what does 'herstory' mean to you?" "herstory is recognition that womyn in the past have done extraordinary things to get us where we are today. herstory means that our past is not written by men or that our past is not only remembered by men. it is to say that although you have had the power to try and tell us who we were (through your textbooks, your media and your stories of glory) we choose not to let such power control how we remember ourselves. that power cannot and will not shape how i retell the contributions womyn have made to this world. 
herstory is to #sayhername
herstory is to recognize #metoo
herstory is to show how she persisted

tweet_full:
herstory is our story - an ongoing feature of women in the twin cities theater community responding to, "what does 'herstory' mean to you?" "herstory is recognition that womyn in the past have done extraordinary things to get us where we are today. herstory means that our past is not written by men or that our past is not only remembered by men. it is to say that although you have had the power to try and tell us who we were (through your textbooks, your media and your stories of glory) we choose not to let such power control how we remember ourselves. that power cannot and will not shape how i retell the contributions womyn have made to this world.

text:
my character is being tried. but my guides have already let me know to affirm my character with my choices to walk, believe, and love beyond the pathology in my blood that tells me to: *choose people who don't want me nor love me authentically
*remain loyal to people instead of my emotional & spiritual integrity
*bring my clarity into question because an influencer disagrees
*validate my worth based on how the people i love the most treat me

but as i get bigger, i will affirm my own worth with my own creator, thank folks for their time in my life instead of mourning their grand exist, establish and stand firm on my boundaries w/o wavering my needs to accommodate someone's feelings, and finally, i will not only own every experience i've had as woman, but find the love and peace in each and every one of them.

text: one day i plan to share my personal testimony and how it shaped the christian i am today. mike and kathy were a huge part of my faith journey. my heart breaks every time i think about what they went through. iâ€™ve never seen two people have as much faith as they do. kathy told me â€œwhen god closes one door he opens anotherâ€. it took me years to believe because i questioned how could god still be good if he took these two people out of my life. but i learned that jesus was there to hold me when i cried. he was in my passengerâ€™s seat whenever i drove to their old house because i missed our rise and shine breakfasts together. jesus held my hand when i walked into church and felt the loneliest iâ€™d ever been. jesus allowed me to take my anger out on him when he knew who i really wanted to take my anger out on. he carried me when i didnâ€™t feel like going when my church family was destroyed. one fateful day when i ran into mike and kathy again i learned god had opened a new door for them. god is good even in midst of everything falling apart. in a season, of death, miscarriages, banishment, lies, heartbreak, and betrayal he found a way to show he is good. god didnâ€™t fix my church family but he is still good. i was told i wasnâ€™t allowed to talk about what happened but iâ€™m tired of keeping the secret and pretending this never happened. itâ€™s been 15 years and with the #metoomovement itâ€™s time we stop telling each other what they can and canâ€™t talk about it.  #metoo ##jesuschrist #godisgood  #godisgoodallthetime #believer #christian #personaltestimony

text:
6 years ago at the 5th az inspire: all female open mat, over 90 women from different teams, states, and varying belts and ages gathered to share the mats and bond through this beautiful art. on this day, i would break my silence and speak publicly to share my personal experiences with sexual assault for the very first time. i spoke of the powerlessness, the paralysis, and the guilt, shame, and blame that had trapped me in silence for over a decade. i spoke on how my first experience would set the tone for how i would allow others to treat me and how i would value myself. most importantly, i spoke of how jiu-jitsu helped me to find my voice, find my strength, and find my place so that i could speak without fear in hopes of shining light on an issue filled with darkness. i never understood bravery until the moment i had to look out into a sea of faces, which included young women who were no older than me when i was first assaulted, and share a part of my life that had almost killed me; to willingly accept vulnerability and still smile and promise hope through streams of tears. i often speak of living passionately and with purpose. this was the day that i was able to embrace those words. i am so thankful to the women in this photo and the over 90 women in attendance that day for allowing me to share my story and for helping build this community. together, we are powerful beyond measure. together, we will never have to venture alone. .
.
.

-
-
"the men and children of the village have fled to some other place due to the fear of arrest.

text:
mr. karnataka and mr. whothef*uckareyou! #throwback
i like djokovich/saleh body type over nadal/ronaldo's. so not a fan of bursting muscles. honestly, unless you are a moviestar or an athelete bursting body is not even sexy!

anyway went here because my trainer was competing in this state bodybuilding event, and he invited me. 
i met the guy in the photo- mohammed from mangalore- after he won the championship. he looked a 'he-man' on his beaming 6-packs and exploding muscles, but inside extremely polite.
infact most bodybuilders i know are very mild, compared to their masculine outer. dont know why! 
bodybuilding is so tough- anybody who has ever hit the gym will know what hardcore labour it takes to get even a flat belly, forget the packs.
like everything else in life, the most passionate, focussed and strategic folks deliver, like mohammed.
#metoo working out and hard to craft self a bit :d

text: before the #metoo movement (which was also started by a black woman) there was fannie lou hamer. she spoke to a national audience of physical violence, sexual violence, torture and other abuses for trying to register to vote. she had a constitutional right to vote but she suffered abuse and sexual violence at the hands of the police for trying to do. her story and life are a testament not only to her personal bravery but also to the cruelty sanctioned by the american government. cruelty that she nor many of her cohort received justice or reperations for. in fact despite the wrongness of the abuse she and others faces at the hands of the government to this day calls for restitution to these persons are treated with laughter and unseriousness.  i strongly suggest you read her story in full and look up her famous speech wherein she made famous the phrase â€œiâ€™m sick and tired of being sick and tiredâ€ https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/fannie_lou_hamer

text:
our focus on women's power to ignite social change is not arbitrary... it isn't a fluffy #girlpower thing, nor are we trying to exclude men.
.
we're focused on women because women are the most powerful force for change on the planet.
.
hereâ€™s why:
.
1.  we cannot expect those in power wake-up one day and decide to end the injustices that benefit them.
.
weâ€™ve literally been waiting for that forever. itâ€™s not going to happen unless we make it happen.
.
2.  women are undervalued and underutilized in efforts to make social change.
.
weâ€™re so busy with everything weâ€™re supposed to do and be that weâ€™re too tired to take social action... but it doesn't have to be that way.
.
3.  women are the largest economic growth market in the world.
.
as the worldâ€™s primary consumer, we power the economy. that gives us incredible power to shape global systems.
.
4.  women are the child-bearers & the culture-bearers of our world.â €
.
as the typical primary caretaker for children, both at home and in school, women have a massive amount of power to shape culture for future generations.
.
5.  psychologically speaking, women are uniquely able and statistically more likely to make social change.
.
one study found that â€œwomen are more likely than men to express caring and compassion toward those who are different from themâ€ and that, typically, women more readily embrace diversity, and are more comfortable with complex or messy social concepts.
.
6.  throughout history, women have worked together to push the world toward equality, justice, and peace.
.
there are many examples of thisâ€”most of which were started and/or led by women of color. in the us, we see this in womenâ€™s contribution to ending slavery (particularly the hard work of black women to free their  people), the suffrage movement, the civil rights movement, the womenâ€™s movement, the black lives matter movement (started by three black women), and most recently, the #metoo movement (also started by a black woman.)
.
7.  never in history have women had so much political, social, and intellectual power.
.â €

because i am female
i am expected to aspire to marriage
i am expected to make my life choices
always keeping in mind that
marriage is the most important
now marriage can be a source of
joy and love and mutual support
but why do we teach girls to aspire to marriage
and we don't teach boys the same?
we raise girls to each other as competitors
not for jobs or for accomplishments
which i think can be a good thing
but for the attention of men
we teach girls that they cannot be sexual beings
in the way that boys are

everyone has a past and everyone learns from it. i've learned to give myself grace in my humanness and contiue to learn it. i've learned that i am unique and some people love me for it and others don't; that is a reflection of them, not me. 
the truamatic things from my life do not define me nor did they change my giving, free loving heart. i chose to live for the positive and see the good in everything bc there is always good. 
you chose who you want to be. you have the power to make it happen! you have control of who you are!

text:
monday @viafresno gave me the best send off, which included hawaiian bbq and an affirmation/fill you up circle. while i was crying listening to these wonderful people tell me all the things that they see in me. one thing that was that was said is that i give a voice to people who donâ€™t have one (people of color, women in trauma, low income high risk kids, etc). i realized that i do this because i was in the same shoes a majority of my life. i opened up about my sexual abuse when i was 12 to a school counselor. she never asked any questions, she didnâ€™t ask if he had access to other kids, she didnâ€™t ask if it was still continuing. and so i just buried my trauma and my mind/body coped by forgetting it again. my abuse continued for 6 more years. 
when i had kennedy my abuse flooded my memories and when i came forward again to my parents the response was â€œokaaaay?â€ because it was common knowledge that my paternal grandfather liked little girls but no one did anything about it. so again, i was silenced. my fatherâ€™s response was to move in with my abuser for five years. 
i sat in that for six years. that silence at the hands of my abuser and his placaters hurts. it wasnâ€™t until my abuser tried to pay me a visit to use my bathroom that i found my voice. when he did that my switch flipped; i was loud and vocal and mad. 
as i found my voice several others did too. we were no longer silenced by our relatives and bureaucratic tape. seven other survivors stepped forward and stood in solidarity together. 
and so to bring this back to my point, i am so grateful to have had this path to help be the voice to the silenced and i am so grateful to have a community (you!) that encourages me and stands up for the silenced.  i do this because itâ€™s what jesus did, and he encourages this because thatâ€™s his heart. i invite you to speak up for things that leave your spirit unsettled, itâ€™s unsettled for a reason. â™¥ï¸

text:
at a time when men dominated rock climbing, lynn hill free climbed yosemite national park's feared el capitan wall, ascending 900m of slick granite using only her hands and feet, with no rope assistance. even more impressive was the fact she wasn't just the first woman to scale el capitan, she was the first person to do it full stop. 
hill had been told a woman would never climb a 5.14, had experienced the frustration when her boyfriend received credit in a guidebook for a first free ascent she had actually completed first, and through it all remained unfazed in her belief in the mantra her friend and climbing partner mari gingery once told her: â€œthe rock doesnâ€™t discriminate.â€ hill said of the fraternity culture that was, that completing it would change their mindset about what is possibleâ€”particularly for women. not just reaching their level, but going out and saying â€˜me too. i can do thisâ€™ 
a warrior for women everywhere ğŸ’ª

tarana burke is an african-american civil rights activist from the bronx, new york who founded the me too movement. in 2006, burke began using the phrase "me too" to raise awareness of the pervasiveness of sexual abuse and assault in society, and the phrase developed into a broader movement, following the 2017 use of #metoo as a hashtag following the harvey weinstein sexual abuse allegations. time named burke, among a group of other prominent activists dubbed "the silence breakers", as the time person of the year for 2017. source: wikipedia  @taranajaneen

text:
78/100 ::the truth of pain:: at the twilight of processing my abuse i was rocking my new born, a nameless agony bubbling from my core, pushing to the surface for the first time. sobbing, i found myself singingâ€”a wordless song of pure guttural grief. it began a hum and expanded as i rose and fell on the waves of pain. it kept me afloat and swimming through instead of swallowed whole, turning my unspeakable pain into rhythm, a river i could step into to move me through. it held hope, movementâ€”my baby slept peacefully despite my tornado of mourning.
.
i remember the low moans of my childbirth, the way it helped cope with the intense pain of contraction.
.
then i thought my singing was strange, i would have been embarrassed if witnessed. today i see that song as intuitive medicine, the wisdom that we hold, our language to process our trauma, to exorcise our pain. we hold our own path to the light.
.
survivors of child abuse and rape are taught our pain doesnâ€™t exist, that our suffering isnâ€™t real. it takes time to acknowledge and feel our pain, to allow it in so it can flow out of us. we pushed it down until it became a cancer, itâ€™s symptoms projected and refracted into ailments that torture our body and mystify our mind. that is pain suffocatedâ€”pain expressed is contraction, expression that makes way for birth and new life.
.
my heart is with the scores of women and children who were forced to drive their pain underground until it manifested diseaseâ€”called crazy, hysterical, mentally illâ€”as their trauma fractured and distorted them. our society canâ€™t yet see past our coping to the depths at which we have been poisoned, it blames the victim and misses the miracle of our survival. yet our pain is real and it deserves space and air to be drawn out, to sing its song out loud, to be laid in the sunlight and warmed to life, melted down until itâ€™s pure essence is left, a golden nugget of strength: the incredible love for ourself and this world that called us to survive. itâ€™s the density of steelâ€”our will. when our pain passes and returns to the soil, whatâ€™s left is our gold to harvest, our means to thriveâ€”when fear subsides all i can see is itâ€™s overflowing abundance.

text:
this is what i was wearing. this was the birthday i will never forget. january 1st, 2019 between the hours of 3am and 5am was the night i was sexually assaulted. this outfit laid in the bottom of my hamper for over a month. i couldn't look at it. i kept having dreams about it. this was the night where i learned who my true friends were. this was the night that defined my relationships in my family. i learned that i couldn't trust anyone. i won't lie and say that i'm stronger because of this. i'm not. i'm afraid to go to sleep at night. i'm afraid of bathrooms and taking showers. i have to lock the door to my room at night. my arm wasn't fully functional for a day due to vaccines and i had a full blown panic attack because i felt defenseless. i cant listen to "22" by taylor swift because i listened to it that night. i never want to celebrate my birthday again. 
but i will say that i've learned a lot. i've learned to value myself. i've learned that "family" is just a term, and those who are there for you wont necessarily be "family." i've learned how much people victim blame. "you could have done something." "you should have known your _____ wouldn't protect you." "didnt he(the perpetrator) know youre dating someone?" "why didn't you do xyz?" it's never the victim's fault, and anyone who thinks that can fuck off. i learned how amazing it feels to tell my story and that people will listen and care. i learned the value of therapy and a good therapist. i learned that despite my world being shattered, i can start a new, beautiful world.

i'm sharing my story now because i'm farther removed from it, but i'm by no means over it. i want others to know that they're not alone. i'm also sharing this because i wont hide any longer. i wont make excuses for the asshole who did it nor for those who victim blame, who minimize sexual assault, who have invalidated me.

i am a survivor. i am strong. i am brave. and i am done with society's bullshit.

#metoo #survivor

text:
this is sickening. the reason why this keeps on happening, why we still have such rape culture in our society is because itâ€™s so ingrained into us. we donâ€™t give perpetrators the correct punishment, the right punishment. there are more drug dealers in prison than rapists. the reason why rape stats and hate crime stats are so high is because the justice system, us as a society havenâ€™t given the right response to stuff like this, havenâ€™t made it a despicable, heinous crime like it is. we let people off, in this case the university have turned a blind eye, we just justify it in the name of â€˜free speechâ€™, â€˜it was a mistake why are we going to ruin their lives over itâ€™ or â€˜they didnâ€™t actually do anythingâ€™. we as a society fail survivors and victims of hate crimes, rape because we ignore the signs leading up to it. we ignore the actual crime.  we donâ€™t give a deserving punishment, we donâ€™t isolate them from our society, we donâ€™t try and change them. we donâ€™t teach our children acceptance and love enough. we donâ€™t place boundaries on people with the â€˜jokesâ€™ they tell of their actions. we need to call it all out, the actions, the jokes, the crime. we shouldnâ€™t stand for a little bit of â€˜sexismâ€™ or hate. we need to show people as a society, this is unacceptable. â€˜they couldnâ€™t have done thisâ€™. we paint this imagine of this â€˜correctâ€™ perpetrator and we compare it to the then assailants. there is no perfect perpetrator. there is no perfect victim. there is no perfect crime. so before it even gets to that stage, stop the jokes, the actions, the people before itâ€™s too late.

text:

text:
to illustrate my point let me tell you some things about me. i had a rough childhood, was on the streets by 15, and i did some questionable shit in those years, no doubt. but what i learned during that time was invaluable to me in this #metoo era:
.
1. let people know that if they fuck with you, there will be severe consequences.
.
2. strike fear into the hearts of those who would harm you. being agreeable is a skill. being crazy is a skill. being unpredictable is the greatest skill of all. learn them all because you will need them for safety.
.
3. the fastest way to evening the playing field between a 200lb man and a 105lb woman is with a weapon. #2a
.
i was raped as a child. young girls are taught to go along to get along. we are taught to look pretty and dance with strangers, even if itâ€™s uncomfortable. we are taught that itâ€™s unladylike to scream, and to curse, and to fight. what we arenâ€™t taught is the power of our own voices and how to create personal boundaries. we donâ€™t need men to protect us. we need to learn to protect ourselves. this is only half the battle.
.
emasculating young men leads to bottled up aggression. not having friendly touch will do the same. this is why i am a huge fan of contact sports, especially jiu jitsu and wrestling. it is a natural behavior expressed in male adolescents. the bullies, btw, need wrestling and contact sports the most as an outlet. donâ€™t simply take pity on the kid getting beat up, thereâ€™s some shit going on under the hood of the bully too.
.
if you put touch-starved boys with bottled-up aggression into a world full of girls who were raised to be â€œladylikeâ€ and not fight, scream, curse, and threaten your life if you violate boundaries, do you know what youâ€™ll get? a #metoo movement.
.
this isnâ€™t getting solved with a fucking gilette advertisement for razors. itâ€™s like the d.a.r.e program which was ideologically supported but totally counterproductive in reality. so fathers, raise your daughters well. mothers, raise your sons well. foster self-confidence in your children and raise children who know how to create healthy boundaries and youâ€™ll make a generation that will change the world.

text:
"in april 1848, mary & emily fled enslavement aboard a ship called the pearl. at the ages of 15 & 13, they were just 2 of the 70 black people that escaped enslavement. their ship left d.c., under the cover of darkness, but was forced to drop anchor while still in southern waters after encountering heavy winds on the chesapeake bay. the delay allowed enough time for a steamboat to catch the pearl & capture those on board, who were brought back to d.c. & sold back into slavery. a month later mary & emily were in the hold of another ship, the union, heading south to new orleans for sale. 
because of their youth, beauty, & light skin tone, the edmonson sisters fell under the slave market category of â€œfancy girls,â€ a euphemism for sex slaves, and a high price of $1200 each was set for them (a high sum for female slaves during this period). mary & emilyâ€™s father, paul edmonson, worked alongside william chaplin & other prominent abolitionists to raise the money needed to purchase their freedom. at a time when the widespread sexual exploitation of enslaved  black women in the south was not well-known in the north, the edmonson sisters became powerful symbols of the dangers that slavery posed for women. collections taken up by white parishioners (a very rare act) & abolitionists on their behalf were sufficient to secure the sistersâ€™ freedom in november of 1848.

following their emancipation, mary and emily were active among the northern abolitionist set. they moved to new york state, attended school, & worked with their father to free their still-enslaved siblings. at an 1850 antislavery meeting in cazenovia, new york, they flanked frederick douglass while one of the sistersâ€”most likely the elder maryâ€”spoke out against the imprisonment of william chaplin just days before. for a black woman to address a crowd at a time when some abolitionists, & many americans, felt that women should not speak in public. the edmonson sisters later enrolled at oberlin college in ohio. soon after their arrival, mary died of tuberculosis and a grieving emily returned to washington, d.c. she became a teacher at a school for black women, continued her abolitionist advocacy, started a family.â€

text:
ğŸ‘ new episode sponsored by @sudio: healing as a survivor ğŸ‘
.
content warning: sexual assault
.
years before the online #metoo movement that took place in october 2017, yee xiong filed a civil suit case against her attacker. determined to bring justice to her case, she bravely held her ground despite the bribery and threats that occurred during the conviction. it was only a few months later that yee reached out to me to again to share news of her huge win of her lawsuit case. the legal battle lasted for 6 years. according to a ny times interview, yee hopes that her victory will send â€œa very powerful and positive message to the world that people will be held accountable for their actions, no matter how long it takes.â€
.
in this episode, yee will share with us how she navigated through the legalities of her case and healed herself after the incident. on a larger scale, we also will discuss about how sexual violence is related to immigration rights.
.
yee xiong is a daughter of hmong refugee parents and an advocate for sexual assault survivors and immigrant rights. she earned her ba in asian american studies at the university of california, davis, and works as a community educator at her local rape crisis center in yolo county. she is passionate about building solidarity among historically oppressed communities through grassroots organizing, women and youth of color empowerment, southeast asian and migrant worker issues, and ethnic studies.
.
follow yee on instagram @yee.speaks!
.

don't miss metoo founder tarana burke at the 8th annual toronto black film festival on february 16, 9pm at isabel bader theatre. tickets => torontoblackfilm.com

she is one of time magazine's 100 most influential people in 2018, who will receive tbff 2019 social impact award during an intimate evening where she'll share her journey as women rights advocate. moderated by festival founder @fabienne_colas.

tarana burke created the #metoo movement in 2006 in order to help young women of color who have survived sexual abuse. her movement has been instrumental in bringing sexual harassment and assault to the forefront today.

hurry, grab your tickets quickly for that one of kind inspiring night! => torontoblackfilm.com .

we are part of and experiencing a cosmic evolution of and on all things, all understanding, all revealing. we are opening pathways into greater and greater awarenesses because our desire for "this time to be done", a time of dwelling within a fictional existence, of belief structures and call forth that which really is. the end of rule within the religious belief systems that define characters of hierarchy and transform these beliefs into a complete and total opposite where all things are equal. 
we are transcending through healing, and we are soon to be re-united with that which we are, fully integrated with self for there is only one.

text:
martial arts has changed my life. today i drove to downtown la for a workshop. i parked my car in a parking garage, walked past many questionable individuals and i noticed a few men following me for a bit when walking to and from the workshop space and my car.
â €
a year ago my heart would have been pounding. i would have called josiah to stay on the phone with me while i walked to and from my car, i would have been shaken up and looking over my shoulder every two seconds. â €
â €
this year iâ€™m different, and i owe it all to bjj and muay thai.
â €
i donâ€™t really train for the same reasons other people do and iâ€™ve never really become a fanatic. â €
â €
i train for moments like today. so i can feel a calm heart rate and a cool head when i feel those little hairs on the back of my neck stand up and i see a guy following me from my peripheral vision.
â €
i train to feel empowered, and i felt that today. â €
â €
i still have so much to learn and so many areas of improvement, but it will come in time. for now, iâ€™m celebrating the victory of being less afraid and more empowered to physically protect myself. â €
just because youâ€™ve been a victim, doesnâ€™t mean you have to stay a victim. if youâ€™ve had an experience and you want to train to help gain your power back, please message me. or better yet, come to a class with me. iâ€™ll drill with you and stay by your side. you donâ€™t have to do it alone. â € â €

text:
the me too movement, from an outside perspective (and as a man), seems to be about more than justice or equality, but about support.  itâ€™s a demonstration of solidarity for each of the women who have come forward with their stories as a means to shine a light on a dark part of their experience; itâ€™s about sparking discussions about deep societal problems we have as a whole and itâ€™s about giving permission to all those who have experienced something similar that itâ€™s okay to speak up. itâ€™s meant to show those whose own lives have been touched by such evil that they are not alone, and to emphatically state to those who marginalize women in this way, that it is clearly not okay or acceptable any longer.

the womenâ€™s march is such a powerful event for both women and men.  we must all send the message that we are there for â€˜herâ€™, whomever she may be.  it is critical that we as men (and women) speak up when we see something untoward, avoid actions that cross the line of appropriate behavior, and be more aware of how our own actions affect others.  to march and show support, to speak up, and to promote a future of true equality is the highest calling for any citizen of this country. as a man who has never been harassed or assaulted, i can never relate to what these women have gone through, but i wish them peace and strength through their trials.  i can, however, pledge to lend my support in any way i can, to ensure that we have a country where everyone is heard, respected, and equal.

#repost @backto_muslimidentity
â€¢ â€¢ â€¢
perempuan butuh syariat islam, bukan ruu pks
.
pengamat politik dan pemerhati perempuan, pratama julia sunjandari, menilai alasan tingginya angka kekerasan seksual di indonesia yang menjadi latar belakang legalisasi rancangan undang undang (ruu) penghapusan kekerasan seksual (pks) sungguh mengada-ada.

pasalnya, menurut pratma, bukan sekadar ada umbrella act lalu persoalan kekerasan seksual selesai. perancis yang telah mengatur tentang sanksi kriminal pelecehan seksual di tempat kerja menunjukkan pejabat dunia christine lagarde yang juga mantan menkeu pransis pernah menjadi korban pelecehan seksual bersama puluhan mantan perempuan terkemuka prancis lainnya. atau gerakan #metoo yang kini mendunia menunjukkan bahwa hukum di negara-negara tersebut tidak mampu menghentikan kekerasan seksual.

pratma lalu mengungkap tiga alasan kalangan feminis ngotot ingin melegalisasi ruu pks, â€œpertama menyuburkan perilaku sekuler liberal. muatan srhr (sexual and reproductive healths rights) sebagai â€˜amanahâ€™ beijing platform for action (bpfa) amat kuat. frasa â€˜kontrol seksualâ€™ itu menegaskan daulat atas tubuh sehingga seorang istri berhak menolak hamil atau menolak ajakan suaminya ke tempat tidur. termasuk hak untuk meluapkan orientasi seksual pada apapun atau siapapun.â€ kedua, kata pratma julia, merusak keluarga terutama relasi suami istri. tak ada lagi qawwam (pemimpin) dalam rumah tangga termasuk dalam hubungan yang amat privat. ketiga, menikam syariat islam. kalangan liberal, dengan dukungan negara leluasa mengadvokasi umat untuk tidak lagi patuh pada hukum allah. â€œmenjadi keharusan bagi kaum muslimin untuk menolak dan mencegah kemunkaran ini dengan aksi nyata,â€ ungkapnya kepada mnews, rabu (30/1/2019). pratma kemudian menjelaskan bahwa umat islam harus berupaya menegakkan syariat islam kaffah sebagai solusi persoalan kekerasan terhadap perempuan, â€œtidak kalah penting mengedukasi umat bahwa persoalan kekerasan seksual, bahkan pelecehan kehormatan perempuan tak akan terjadi jika khilafah tegak. syariat kaffah itu memiliki hukum yang amat memuliakan manusia apalagi perempuan dengan hukum-hukum sistem pergaulannya,â€ tukasnya.[] sumber:www.musli

#metoo in india: the women left behind
#
image copyright puneet barnala image caption domestic maids and other women in india's informal sectors are particularly vulnerable india's #metoo campaign has taken off in fits and starts but it has still not touched the lives of millions of poor, vulnerable women who work in informal jobs, writes professor sreeparna chattopadhyay.meena (her name has been changed on request) is a 45-year-old domestic worker in the southern city of bangalore. and she is a survivor of sexual harassment in the workplace. she cooks and cleans in three different homes, earning around 6,000 rupees ($84; $64) a month. she used to earn nearly three times as much. but she lost her job in several homes after she accused one of her employers of sexually harassing her. bhanwari devi: the rape that led to india's sexual harassment lawmeena said the harassment started after she borrowed 100,000 rupees for her older daughter's wedding from a couple in their early 70s. she had been working in their house for three years by then. she alleged the man would initially try and brush past her while she was sweeping or mopping the floor. sometimes, she said, he would try and touch her casually or even tugâ€¦

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since day one.

steve bannon left the wh august 2017 and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? 'j-c' church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt, with the goonsquad known as gop, has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagateâ„¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since day one.

steve bannon left the wh august 2017 and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? 'j-c' church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt, with the goonsquad known as gop, has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagateâ„¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are useless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is no way that gop isn't aware of this - after all, cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got as cambridge analytica. pedofiles - i bet - but the way things are bundled sure makes goebbels shiver.

trump plays along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still - the republicans willingly piggybacked this before the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt, with the goonsquad known as gop, has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

text:
for years, americans have shrugged their shoulders over nsa surveillance and government access to digital data and said, â€œi donâ€™t care; i have nothing to hide.â€ now they are starting to see that maybe they do have something to hide. they are starting to understand that their own preferences and those of their friends and family can be hoovered up and stored in perpetuity and fed through algorithms to produce manipulative messaging intended to move beliefs and influence actions.

although regulators and state attorneys general are launching investigations, the real hammer will be the market. whether it is facebook, twitter, or some other social media platform, when users start to realize that the data they are sharing may be used against them or cause them to lose control over their beliefs or be manipulated, they will begin to shut off. if the company canâ€™t be trusted with personal data, users simply will not use that platform and advertisers will go elsewhere.

roger mcnamee, mark zuckerbergâ€™s long-time mentor, saw the risk early on and tried to get facebook executives to manage it, but his warnings fell on deaf ears.  in an interview with christiane amanpour, mcnamee said that in october 2016, he personally warned zuckerberg and sheryl sandberg of the magnitude of the risk, but failed to get their attention. according to mcnamee, facebookâ€™s leaders kept arguing that facebook is a platform company, not a media company and â€œweâ€™re not responsible for what third parties do.â€ mcnamee warned them then, - you have 1.7 billion members and if they decide you are responsible, it wonâ€™t matter what the law says.

jody westby
forbes

i've watched the qspiracy since day one.

steve bannon left the wh august 2017 and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? 'j-c' church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt, with the goonsquad known as gop, has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagateâ„¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are useless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is no way that gop isn't aware of this - after all, cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got as cambridge analytica. pedofiles - i bet - but the way things are bundled sure makes goebbels shiver.

trump plays along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still - the republicans willingly piggybacked this before the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

i tell him that another former employee described the firm as â€œmi6 for hireâ€, and iâ€™d never quite understood it.
.
- itâ€™s like dirty mi6 because youâ€™re not constrained. thereâ€™s no having to go to a judge to apply for permission. itâ€™s normal for a â€˜market research companyâ€™ to amass data on domestic populations. and if youâ€™re working in some country and thereâ€™s an auxiliary benefit to a current client with aligned interests, well thatâ€™s just a bonus.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
throughout the committee hearing, several republican senators including ted cruz and thom tillis pointed to the obama campaignâ€™s use of facebook data, to highlight the fact that such practices are bipartisan.

however, people who downloaded the obama campaign app were aware they were using a political app. by contrast, the data obtained by cambridge analytica was obtained via a personality quiz application whose users had no idea their data would be used by a political campaign.

cambridge analytica improperly obtained the personal information of millions of facebook users to build profiles of us voters in order to target them with personalised political advertisements, via a related uk-based entity called scl elections.
.
- we exploited facebook to harvest millions of peopleâ€™s profiles, said wylie in march. - and built models to exploit what we knew about them and target their inner demons. that was the basis the entire company was built on.

wylie has previously told mps at a british select committee that the eu referendum was won through fraud after vote leave allegedly used a network of companies to get round election spending laws. he said he thought there â€œcould have been a different outcome had there not been, in my view, cheatingâ€. he also met privately with house democrats in april, but wednesdayâ€™s hearing was his first public appearance before us lawmakers.

olivia solon
the guardian

text:
u.s. president donald trump's former aide steve bannon sought to use personal information collected online to promote "a culture war," a whistleblower on now-defunct political data firm cambridge analytica told u.s. senators on wednesday.

bannon, a former cambridge analytica vice president, "saw cultural warfare as a means to create enduring change in american politics," testified christopher wylie, who says information about tens of millions of facebook users ended up in cambridge analytica's hands.

bannon's attorney william burck did not immediately respond to an email request for comment on wylie's testimony.

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
on april 16, 2017, in the village of shambhupura in banswara, rajasthan, india, kachru, 21, and monica, 19, got married and were cousins but there family, was not fine with it. the couple were paraded naked, beaten, and sexually assaulted by the whole village of shambhupura and family members including their fathers, brothers and, uncles. the accused have been booked for rioting,Â wrongful restraint and confinement, wrongly causing hurt, attempted murder, and sexual harassment.
-
-
"the men and children of the village have fled to some other place due to the fear of arrest.
according to the police, on thursday, varaseng resident varanseng resident lord ratna maida, twenty-four-year-old padla resident shankar son lalji, kundelia resident forgotten wife dhulia, resident of shambhupura, gutu son shyama, subhash son hiraji, kangi son kalu, dilip son chetan, ramatu wife kalu and bhusli wife bheema was arrestedÂ earlier, nine people including the father of the girl were arrested on wednesday."

text:
aviation: the moon reflecting over still water (5/10) by nicholas jones, 30 january 2015. -

dear children,

i would be lying if i said,
i didnâ€™t think about him,
every now and then,

because in just a couple weeks,
the day will come when,
it will have been a year,
since the first time that i held him,

and i wouldnâ€™t be telling the truth,
if i said i wasnâ€™t used,
to the heartache and heartbreak, that comes with love and loss,
and the perpetual amount of dreams undone,

and thereâ€™s still so much,
that i never said,
running through my head,
forever chasing the sun.

sincerely,
the moon reflecting over still water. -

text:
on april 16, 2017, in the village of shambhupura in banswara, rajasthan, india, kachru, 21, and monica, 19, got married and were cousins but there family, was not fine with it. the couple were paraded naked, beaten, and sexually assaulted by the whole village of shambhupura and family members including their fathers, brothers and, uncles. the accused have been booked for rioting,Â wrongful restraint and confinement, wrongly causing hurt, attempted murder, and sexual harassment.
-
-
"the men and children of the village have fled to some other place due to the fear of arrest.
according to the police, on thursday, varaseng resident varanseng resident lord ratna maida, twenty-four-year-old padla resident shankar son lalji, kundelia resident forgotten wife dhulia, resident of shambhupura, gutu son shyama, subhash son hiraji, kangi son kalu, dilip son chetan, ramatu wife kalu and bhusli wife bheema was arrestedÂ earlier, nine people including the father of the girl were arrested on wednesday."

text:
aviation: time is a straight line (6/10) by nicholas jones, 29 january 2017. -

time is,
a straight,
line,

you can,
retrace,
as much,
and as often,
as you want,

but you,
can never,
change what was,
into what is,
when the past and the present,
stand at opposing ends,

but damn if you cant try. -

text:
for victim-survivors of abuse, both violent and non-violent, an incredibly high proportion report that their appearance was a way that perpetrators made them feel powerless or deserving of abuse. 
women and femmes in particular experience ubiquitous pressure from society to have a low weight and maintain conventional beauty standards. 
abusers know this and take advantage of the things that we are most sensitive about.

text:
resilience: memoir of a broken little girl discovering a woman of strength and beauty (autobiography)

in her debut memoir, toni talks candidly about her colourful life. this powerful account is an unexpected page turner that will have you on the edge of your seat wondering what happens next.

from her early childhood battle with a congenital facial defect, through debilitating battles in school to her traumatic entry into the adult world. it details her struggle with anxiety and depression, low self esteem and a longing for love and happiness.

being released into the slipstream of the #metoo movement this gripping memoir details toniâ€™s own traumatic incidences of assault and openly questions the time in her life when consent and respectful relationships where not talked about.

the book chronicles her battle to get justice for her family in the wake of her daughterâ€™s abuse disclosure and her personal battle to help, heal and free her daughter from the impacts of that abuse.

toniâ€™s writing displays a vulnerability and truthfulness that is as courageous as it is inspirational. itâ€™s a powerful testament of her strength and resilience, showing all of us that peace and happiness is obtainable, no matter how our lives unfold.

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
u.s. president donald trump's former aide steve bannon sought to use personal information collected online to promote "a culture war," a whistleblower on now-defunct political data firm cambridge analytica told u.s. senators on wednesday.

bannon, a former cambridge analytica vice president, "saw cultural warfare as a means to create enduring change in american politics," testified christopher wylie, who says information about tens of millions of facebook users ended up in cambridge analytica's hands.

bannon's attorney william burck did not immediately respond to an email request for comment on wylie's testimony.

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

mark hosenball
reuters

#reposted from @muslimahnewsid - / perempuan butuh syariat islam, bukan ruu pks /
.
pengamat politik dan pemerhati perempuan, pratama julia sunjandari, menilai alasan tingginya angka kekerasan seksual di indonesia yang menjadi latar belakang legalisasi rancangan undang undang (ruu) penghapusan kekerasan seksual (pks) sungguh mengada-ada.
.
pasalnya, menurut pratma, bukan sekadar adaÂ umbrella actÂ lalu persoalan kekerasan seksual selesai. perancis yang telah mengatur tentang sanksi kriminal pelecehan seksual di tempat kerja menunjukkan pejabat dunia christine lagarde yang juga mantan menkeu pransis pernah menjadi korban pelecehan seksual bersama puluhan mantan perempuan terkemuka prancis lainnya atau gerakanÂ #metooÂ yang kini mendunia menunjukkan bahwa hukum di negara-negara tersebut tidak mampu menghentikan kekerasan seksual.
.
pratma lalu mengungkap tiga alasan kalangan feminis ngotot ingin melegalisasi ruu pks, â€œpertama menyuburkan perilaku sekuler liberal. muatan srhr (sexual and reproductive healths rights) sebagai â€˜amanahâ€™Â beijing platform for actionÂ (bpfa) amat kuat. frasa â€˜kontrol seksualâ€™ itu menegaskan daulat atas tubuh sehingga seorang istri berhak menolak hamil atau menolak ajakan suaminya ke tempat tidur. termasuk hak untuk meluapkan orientasi seksual pada apapun atau siapapun.â€
.
kedua, kata pratma julia, merusak keluarga terutama relasi suami istri. tak ada lagiÂ qawwamÂ (pemimpin) dalam rumah tangga termasuk dalam hubungan yang amat privat. ketiga, menikam syariat islam. kalangan liberal, dengan dukungan negara leluasa mengadvokasi umat untuk tidak lagi patuh pada hukum allah.
.
â€œmenjadi keharusan bagi kaum muslimin untuk menolak dan mencegah kemunkaran ini dengan aksi nyata,â€ ungkapnya kepadaÂ mnews, rabu (30/1/2019).
.
.

text:
blank canvas. .
.
.
.
i'm clean of what happened to me. scars of mental damage will always be there but i am learning jumps to your loops and hoops to fight off my anxiety, my eating disorder, my fear of people getting to close, my unraveling of learned norms that are not norms, and my suppress memories coming at me in waves of torture sinking my little boat of hope. 
but i am still a blank canvas if you paint white all over the pain.

text:
i keep fixating on the idea of escaping - from meaningless responsibilities, well-meant expectations, and too-meaningful relationships. the desire is total isolation; except for my four-legged companion whose unconditional love is the only painless one that i know. i dream of engulfing myself in an uninhabited, vast natural landscape that offers freedom, quietness and exploration: a sanctuary for my soul. ~copingdiary ~
~
~
~
